  Watch the branches carefully. Do any move when the wind isn't blowing?</p>
  
  <p><strong>ðŸ‘‚ Listen</strong><br>
  Do you hear a tiny splash? Or a plop that doesn't sound like rain?</p>
  
  <p><strong>ðŸ‘ƒ Smell</strong><br>
  Forests smell like trees, water, and dirt doing their jobs.</p>
  
  <p><strong>âœ‹ Feel</strong><br>
  Touch bark, rocks, and leaves - but not branches over the stream. Tree trout like their space.</p>

  <h2>Step 3: Ask Important Questions</h2>
  <p>Good forest explorers ask questions like:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>"What lives up there?"</li>
    <li>"Why is that branch wet?"</li>
    <li>"Could a fish climb that tree if it really wanted to?"</li>
  </ul>
  <p>There are no wrong answers (except yelling).</p>

  <h2>Step 4: Leave No Trace (Especially for Fish)</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Don't throw things</li>
    <li>Don't climb trees near water</li>
    <li>Don't try to catch anything you're not sure exists</li>
  </ul>
  <p>Tree trout feel safest when people are kind, calm, and slightly unsure.</p>

  <h2>Explorer Bonus Activity</h2>
  <p>After your walk, draw:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>What you think a tree trout looks like</li>
    <li>OR what you almost saw</li>
    <li>OR the tree where one might live</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Remember</h2>
  <p>Sometimes the most important thing you find in the forest is a good question.</p>
  <p>And sometimes, just maybe, it's a fish in a tree.</p>
